# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters allowed cultivation at much greater heights and made land more productive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open-field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism from the twelfth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] New monastic orders such as the Cistercians became major landholders and sheep farmers, particularly in the Borders where they were organised in granges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the late Medieval period, most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams, allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, known as husbandmen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised for meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The rural economy appears to have boomed in the thirteenth century and in the immediate aftermath of the Black Death was still buoyant, but by the 1360s there was a severe falling off in incomes to be followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is roughly half the size of England and Wales and has approximately the same amount of coastline, but only between a fifth and a sixth of the amount of the arable or good pastoral land, under 60 metres above sea level, and most of this is located in the south and east.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This made marginal pastoral farming and fishing, the key factors in the pre-modern economy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Its east Atlantic position means that it has moderate rainfall: today about 700 mm per year in the east and over 1,000 mm in the west.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This encouraged the spread of blanket peat bog, the acidity of which, combined with high level of wind and salt spray, made most of the western islands treeless.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The existence of hills, mountains, quicksands and marshes made agriculture and internal communication difficult.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early Middle Ages, from the fifth century to the tenth century, were a period of climate deterioration, with a drop in temperature and an increase in rainfall, resulting in more land becoming unproductive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of significant transport links and wider markets, most farms had to produce a self-sufficient diet of meat, dairy products and cereals, supplemented by hunter-gathering.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The climate meant that more oats and barley were grown than wheat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The evidence of bones indicates that cattle were by far the most important domesticated animal, followed by pigs, sheep and goats, while domesticated fowl were very rare.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Christian missionaries from Ireland may have changed agricultural practice, bringing innovations such as the horizontal watermill and mould board ploughs, which were more effective in turning the soil.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the period 1150 to 1300, warm dry summers and less severe winters of the Medieval Warm Period allowed cultivation at much greater heights above sea level and made land more productive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Arable farming grew significantly, but was still more common in low-lying areas in the south and east than in high-lying areas such as the Highlands, Galloway and the Southern Uplands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The feudalism introduced under David I, particularly in the east and south where the crown's authority was greatest, saw the placement of baronial lordships.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Land was now held from the king, or a superior lord, in exchange for loyalty and forms of service that were usually military.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Barons, who held feudal tenures, had the right to hold baronial courts, which could deal with matters of land ownership.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the imposition of feudalism continued to sit beside the existing systems of landholding and tenure and it is not clear how this change impacted on the lives of the ordinary free and unfree workers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In places, feudalism may have tied workers more closely to the land.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, the predominantly pastoral nature of Scottish agriculture may have made the imposition of a manorial system, based on the English model, impracticable in some areas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Obligations appear to have been limited to occasional labour service, seasonal renders of food, hospitality and money rents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually included supplying oxen for ploughing the lord's land on an annual basis and the much resented obligation to grind corn at the lord's mill.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Hunting reserves were adopted by Anglo-Norman lords and then by Gaelic ones, creating large tracts of land reserved for the leisure of the aristocracy and nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were less rigorously enforced than in England, where the taking of wood and game were strictly forbidden, and all royal forests were on land already in the king's hands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of new monastic orders such as the Cistercians in this period also brought innovations in agriculture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Particularly in the Borders, their monasteries became major landholders, sheep farmers and producers of wool for the markets in Flanders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were organised in granges, monastic farms run by lay brothers of the order.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Granges were theoretically within 30 miles of the mother monastery, so that those working there could return for services on Sundays and feast days.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were used for variety of purposes, including pastoral, arable and industrial production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, to manage more distant assets in Ayrshire, Melrose Abbey used Mauchline as a "super grange", to oversee lesser granges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Some abbeys like Melrose had at least 12,000 sheep in the late thirteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The system of infield and outfield agriculture, a variation of open field farming widely used across Europe, may have been introduced with feudalism and would continue until the eighteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This expanded from the use of small enclosed fields, which continued from the prehistoric era.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The infield was the best land, close to housing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was farmed continuously and most intensively, receiving most of the manure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crops were usually bere (a form of barley), oats and sometimes wheat, rye and legumes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The more extensive outfield was used for largely for oats.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It was fertilised from the overnight folding of cattle in the summer and was often left fallow to recover its fertility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In fertile regions the infield could be extensive, but in the uplands it might be small, surrounded by large amounts of outfield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In coastal areas fertiliser included seaweed and around the major burghs urban refuse was used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Yields were fairly low, often around three times the quantity of seed sown, although they could reach twice that yield on some infields.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The main unit of land measurement in Scotland was the *davoch* (i.e.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This unit is also known as the "Scottish ploughgate".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In English-speaking Lothian, it was simply a ploughgate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have measured about 104 acres (0.42 km2), divided into 4 *raths* or eight *oxgangs*, the area that eight oxen were said to be able to plough in one year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By the fourteenth century most farming was based on the Lowland fermtoun or Highland baile, settlements of a handful of families that jointly farmed an area notionally suitable for two or three plough teams.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were allocated in run rigs to tenant farmers, who were usually known as husbandmen or bonders.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The average amount of land used by a husbandman in Scotland, known as a husbandland, was 26 acres, or 2 oxgangs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They would also have had a share of hay meadow and common pasture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Below the husbandmen, lesser landholders and free tenants, were the cottars, who often shared rights to common pasture, occupied small portions of land and participated in joint farming as hired labour.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Farms also might have grassmen, who had rights only to grazing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Pasture was often accessed by shieling-grounds, with shelters made of stone or turf, used for the grazing of cattle in summer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These would often be distant from the main settlements in the Lowlands, but might be relatively close in the more remote Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Runrigs, were a ridge and furrow pattern, similar to that used in parts of England, with alternating "runs" (furrows) and "rigs" (ridges).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually ran downhill so that they included both wet and dry land, helping to offset some of the problems of extreme weather conditions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Most ploughing was done with a heavy wooden plough with an iron coulter, pulled by oxen, which were more effective on heavy soils and cheaper to feed than horses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were usually pulled by a team of eight oxen, which would have taken four men to operate and only covered half an acre a day.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Key crops included kale (for both humans and animals), and hemp and flax for cloth production.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Sheep and goats were probably the main sources of milk, while cattle were raised primarily for meat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was followed by a slow recovery in the fifteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Towards the end of the period average temperatures began to reduce again, with the cooler and wetter conditions of the Little Ice Age limiting the extent of arable agriculture, particularly in the Highlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The **Anglo-Normans** (Norman: *Anglo-Normaunds*, Old English: *Engel-Norðmandisca*) were the medieval ruling class in the Kingdom of England following the Norman Conquest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] They were primarily a combination of Normans, Bretons, Frenchmen, Flemings, Anglo-Saxons and Celtic Britons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] After the conquest the victorious Normans formed a ruling class in England, distinct from (although intermarrying with) the native Anglo-Saxon and Celtic populations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Over time, their language evolved from the continental Old Norman to the distinct Anglo-Norman language.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Anglo-Normans quickly established control over all of England, as well as parts of Wales (the Welsh-Normans).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] After 1130, parts of southern and eastern Scotland came under Anglo-Norman rule (the Scots-Normans), in return for their support of David I's conquest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Anglo-Norman invasion of Ireland from 1169 saw Anglo-Normans and Cambro-Normans conquer swaths of Ireland, becoming the Irish-Normans.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The composite expression *regno Norman-Anglorum* for the Anglo-Norman kingdom that comprises Normandy and England appears contemporaneously only in the *Hyde Chronicle*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] A small number of Normans had earlier befriended future Anglo-Saxon king of England, Edward the Confessor, during his exile in his mother's homeland of Normandy in northern France.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] When he returned to England, some of them went with him; as such, there were Normans already settled in England before the conquest.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Edward's successor, Harold Godwinson, was defeated by Duke William the Conqueror of Normandy at the Battle of Hastings, leading to William's accession to the English throne.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] After the Norman Conquest of 1066, many of the Anglo-Saxon nobles lost lands and titles; the lesser thegns and others found themselves dispossessed of lands and titles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] A number of free *geburs* had their rights and court access much decreased, becoming unfree *villeins*, despite the fact that this status did not exist in Normandy itself (compared to other "French" regions).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] At the same time, many of the new Norman and Northern-France magnates were distributed lands by the King that had been taken from the English nobles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Some of these magnates used their original French-derived names, with the prefix 'de,' meaning they were lords of the old fiefs in France, and some instead dropped their original names and took their names from new English holdings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Norman conquest of England brought Britain and Ireland into the orbit of the European continent, especially what remained of Roman-influenced language and culture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The England emerging from the Conquest owed a debt to the Romance languages and the culture of ancient Rome.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] It transmitted itself in the emerging feudal world that took its place.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] That heritage can be discerned in language, incorporating the French language and the Roman past, and in the emerging Romanesque (Norman) architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Norman conquest of England also signalled a revolution in military styles and methods.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] A lot of the old Anglo-Saxon military elite began to emigrate, especially the generation next younger to that defeated at Hastings, who had no particular future in a country controlled by the conquerors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] William (and his son, William Rufus), encouraged them to leave, as a security measure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The first to leave went mostly to Denmark and many of these moved on to join the Varangian Guard in Constantinople.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Anglo-Saxons as a whole, for practical reason, however were not demilitarised.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Instead, William arranged for the Saxon infantry to be trained up by Norman cavalry in anti-cavalry tactics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] This led quickly to the establishment of an Anglo-Norman army made up of Norman horsemen of noble blood, Saxon infantrymen often of equally noble blood, assimilated English freemen as rank-and-file, and foreign mercenaries and adventurers from other parts of the Continent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The younger Norman aristocracy showed a tendency towards Anglicisation, adopting such Saxon styles as long hair and moustaches, upsetting the older generation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] (The Anglo-Saxon *cniht* did not take the sense of the French *chevalier* before the latest period of Middle English.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] John Wycliffe (1380s) uses the term *knyytis* generically for men-at-arms, and only in the 15th century did the word acquire the overtones of a noble cavalryman corresponding to the meaning of *chevalier*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Anglo-Norman conquest in the 12th century brought Norman customs and culture to Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The degree of subsequent Norman-Saxon conflict (as a matter of conflicting social identities) is a question disputed by historians.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The 19th-century view was of intense mutual resentment, reflected in the popular legends of Robin Hood and the novel *Ivanhoe* by Sir Walter Scott.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Some residual ill-feeling is suggested by contemporary historian Orderic Vitalis, who in *Ecclesiastical Historii* (1125) wrote in praise of native English resistance to "William the Bastard" (William I of England).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] In order to secure Norman loyalty during his conquest, William I rewarded his loyal followers by taking English land and redistributing it to his knights, officials, and the Norman aristocracy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] In turn, the English hated him, but the king retaliated ruthlessly with his military force to subdue the rebellions and discontentment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Mike Ashley writes on this subject; *"he [William I] may have conquered them [the English], but he never ruled them*".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Not all of the Anglo-Saxons immediately accepted him as their legitimate king.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] As noble families increasingly divided their landholdings between England and Normandy, cross-Channel ties weakened.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] By the 1170s and 1180s, nobles living in England, regardless of origin, identified themselves as English and set themselves apart from foreign-born royal ministers such as William de Longchamp, Philip Mark, and Engelard de Cigogné, who were seen as aliens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] King John and King Henry III's frequent appointment of Poitevin and Savoyard nobles became a focal point for the polarisation between English-born and foreign-born.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Whatever the level of dispute, over time, the two populations intermarried and merged.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Tenants-in-chief following the conquest who married English women included Geofrey de la Guerche, Walter of Dounai and Robert d'Oilly.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Other Norman aristocrats with English wives following the conquest include William Pece, Richard Juvenis and Odo, a Norman knight.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Norman and English distinction appears to disappear towards the end of the 12th century and after the first barons' rebellion and the signing of the Magna Carta, English identity once again triumphed over England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Normans also led excursions into Wales from England and built multiple fortifications as it was one of William's ambitions to subdue the Welsh as well as the English, however, he was not entirely successful.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Afterward, however, the border area known as the Marches was set up and Norman influence increased steadily.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Encouraged by the invasion, monks (usually from France or Normandy) such as the Cistercian Order also set up monasteries throughout Wales.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] By the 15th century a large number of Welsh gentry, including Owain Glyndŵr, had some Norman ancestry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The majority of knights who invaded Ireland were also from or based in Wales (see below).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Anglo-Norman barons also settled in Ireland from the 12th century, initially to support Irish regional kings such as Diarmuid Mac Murchadha whose name has arrived in modern English as Dermot MacMurrough.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Richard de Clare, 2nd Earl of Pembroke, known as "Strongbow", was the leader of the Anglo-Norman Knights whom MacMurrough had requested of Henry II of England to help him to re-establish himself as King of Leinster.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Strongbow died a very short time after invading Ireland but the men he brought with him remained to support Henry II of England and his son John as Lord of Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Chief among the early Anglo-Norman settlers was Theobald Walter (surname Butler) appointed hereditary chief Butler of Ireland in 1177 by King Henry II and founder of one of the oldest remaining British dignities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Most of these Normans came from Wales, not England, and thus the epithet 'Cambro-Normans' is used to describe them by leading late medievalists such as Seán Duffy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] They increasingly integrated with the local Celtic nobility through intermarriage and some accepted aspects of Celtic culture, especially outside the Pale around Dublin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] They are known as *Old English*, but this term came into use to describe them only in 1580, i.e., over four centuries after the first Normans arrived in Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] The Carol was a popular Norman dance in which the leader sang and was surrounded by a circle of dancers who replied with the same song.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] This Norman dance was performed in conquered Irish towns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] David I, who had spent most of his life as an English baron, became king of Scotland in 1124.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] His reign saw what has been characterised as a "Davidian Revolution", by which native institutions and personnel were replaced by English and French ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] Members of the Anglo-Norman nobility took up places in the Scottish aristocracy and he introduced a system of feudal land tenure, which produced knight service, castles and an available body of heavily armed cavalry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] He created an Anglo-Norman style of court, introduced the office of justiciar to oversee justice, and local offices of sheriffs to administer localities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] He established the first royal burghs in Scotland, granting rights to particular settlements, which led to the development of the first true Scottish towns and helped facilitate economic development as did the introduction of the first recorded Scottish coinage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] He continued a process begun by his mother and brothers, of helping to establish foundations that brought the reformed monasticism based on that at Cluny.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] He also played a part in the organisation of diocese on lines closer to those in the rest of Western Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/anglo-normans] These reforms were pursued under his successors and grandchildren Malcolm IV of Scotland and William I, with the crown now passing down the main line of descent through primogeniture, leading to the first of a series of minorities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The first surviving houses in Scotland go back 9500 years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There is evidence of different forms of stone and wooden houses exist and earthwork hill forts from the Iron Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The arrival of the Romans led to the abandonment of many of these forts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the departure of the Romans in the fifth century, there is evidence of the building of a series of smaller "nucleated" constructions sometimes utilizing major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dumbarton.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the following centuries new forms of construction emerged throughout Scotland that would come to define the landscape.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval vernacular architecture utilised local building materials, including cruck constructed houses, turf walls, and clay, with a heavy reliance on stone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval parish church architecture was typically simpler than in England, but there were grander ecclesiastical buildings in the Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From the early fifteenth century, the introduction of Renaissance styles included the selective use of Romanesque forms in church architecture, as in the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Castles arrived in Scotland with the introduction of feudalism in the twelfth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Initially these were wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, but many were replaced by stone castles with a high curtain wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the late Middle Ages, new castles were built, some on a grander scale, and others, particularly in the borders, as simpler tower houses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Gunpowder weaponry led to the use of gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There was a phase of Renaissance palace building from the late fifteenth century, beginning at Linlithgow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The earliest surviving houses in Scotland go back around 9500 years, and the first villages 6000 years; Skara Brae on the Mainland of Orkney is the earliest preserved example in Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Crannogs, or roundhouses, each built on artificial islands, date from the Bronze Age, and stone buildings called Atlantic roundhouses and larger earthwork hill forts from the Iron Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the arrival of the Romans from about 71 AD, they appear to have been largely abandoned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The Romans build military forts like that at Trimontium, and a continuous fortification between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde known as the Antonine Wall, built in the second century AD.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Beyond Roman influence, there is evidence of wheelhouses and underground souterrains.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the departure of the Romans in the third century, there is evidence of the reoccupation of Iron Age forts and of the building of a series of smaller "nucleated" constructions, sometimes utilising major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dumbarton.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval vernacular architecture in rural environments made use of local materials and styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] As in England, cruck construction was used, employing pairs of curved timbers to support the roof; however they were usually hidden from view.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In rural areas there was extensive use of turf to fill in the walls, sometimes on a stone base, but they were not long lasting and had to be rebuilt frequently, perhaps as often as every two or three years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In some regions, including the south-west and around Dundee, solid clay walls were used, or combinations of clay, turf and straw, rendered with clay or lime to make them weatherproof.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] With a lack of long span structural timber, the most common building material was stone, employed in both mortared and dry stone construction.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Different regions used broom, heather, straw, turfs or reeds for roofing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From the twelfth century, burghs, towns that were granted certain legal privileges from the Crown, developed, particularly on the east coast with distinctive urban building patterns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were typically surrounded by a palisade, and many had a castle.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They usually had a market place, with a widened high street or junction, often marked by a mercat cross.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There were houses for the nobles, burgesses and other significant inhabitants, which were often built in a relatively elaborate style and by the end of the period some would have slate roofs or tiles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Very little has survived of the houses of the urban poor.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were probably largely located in the backlands, away from the main street frontages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] From Aberdeen and Perth there is evidence of nearly forty buildings dating from the twelfth to the fourteenth centuries, with walls of planks or wattles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The introduction of Christianity into Scotland from Ireland from the sixth century led to the construction of basic masonry-built churches, beginning on the west coast and islands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Medieval parish church architecture in Scotland was typically much less elaborate than in England, with many churches remaining simple oblongs, without transepts and aisles, and often without towers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the Highlands they were often even simpler, many built of rubble masonry and sometimes indistinguishable from the outside from houses or farm buildings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, from the eighth century, more sophisticated buildings emerged.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Early Romanesque ashlar masonry produced block-built stone buildings, like the eleventh century round tower at Brechin Cathedral and the square towers of Dunblane Cathedral and The Church of St Rule.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the eleventh century, as masonry techniques advanced, ashlar blocks became more rectangular, resulting in structurally more stable walls that could incorporate more refined architectural moulding and detailing that can be seen in corbelling, buttressing, lintels and arching.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] At the same time there were increasing influences from English and continental European designs.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These can be seen in the Romanesque chevron pattern on the piers in the nave of Dunfermline Abbey (1130–40), which were modelled on details from Durham Cathedral.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] St Magnus Cathedral in Orkney, begun in 1137, may have employed masons that had worked at Durham.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The arrival of the new monastic orders in Scotland from the twelfth century led to a boom in ecclesiastical building using English and continental forms, including abbeys at Kelso, Holyrood, Jedburgh and St Andrews.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the thirteenth century, the east end of Elgin Cathedral incorporated typical European Gothic mouldings and tracery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the fifteenth century continental builders are known to have been working in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] French master-mason John Morrow was employed at the building of Glasgow Cathedral and the rebuilding of Melrose Abbey, both considered fine examples of Gothic architecture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The interiors of churches were often elaborate before the Reformation, with highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Deskford and Kinkell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The carvings at Rosslyn Chapel, created in the mid-fifteenth century, elaborately depicting the progression of the seven deadly sins, are considered some of the finest in the Gothic style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Late Medieval Scottish churches also often contained elaborate burial monuments, like the Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Late Gothic architecture saw a contrast with the Perpendicular style used in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This can be seen in the re-adoption of low-massive church building with round arches and pillars, as at the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral, begun in 1406, the facade of St Mary's, Haddington from the 1460s and in the chapel of Bishop Elphinstone's Kings College, Aberdeen (1500–09).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] It may have been influenced by close contacts with Rome and the Netherlands, and was perhaps a conscious reaction against English forms in favour of continental ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] About forty collegiate churches were established in Scotland in the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Many, like Trinity College, Edinburgh, showed a combination of Gothic and Renaissance styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The early sixteenth century saw crown steeples built on churches with royal connections, symbolising imperial monarchy, as at St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is known for its dramatically placed castles, many of which date from the late medieval era.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Castles, in the sense of a fortified residence of a lord or noble, arrived in Scotland as part of David I's encouragement of Norman and French nobles to settle with feudal tenures, particularly in the south and east, and were a way of controlling the contested lowlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These were primarily wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, of a raised mount or motte, surmounted by a wooden tower and a larger adjacent enclosure or bailey, both usually surrounded by a fosse (a ditch) and palisade, and connected by a wooden bridge.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They varied in size from the very large such as the Bass of Inverurie, to more modest designs like Balmaclellan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In England many of these constructions were converted into stone "keep-and-bailey" castles in the twelfth century, but in Scotland most of those that were in continued occupation became stone castles of "enceinte" from the thirteenth century, with a high embattled curtain wall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The need for thick and high walls for defence forced the use of economic building methods, often continuing the tradition of dry-stone rubble building, which were then covered with a lime render, or harled for weatherproofing and a uniform appearance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In addition to the baronial castles there were royal castles, often larger and providing defence, lodging for the itinerant Scottish court and a local administrative centre.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] By 1200 these included fortifications at Ayr and Berwick.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] In the wars of Scottish Independence, Robert I adopted a policy of castle destruction, rather than allow fortresses to be easily retaken and then held by the English, beginning with his own castles at Ayr and Dumfries, and including Roxburgh and Edinburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] After the Wars of Independence, new castles began to be built, often on a grander scale as "livery and maintenance" castles, to house retained troops, like Tantallon, Lothian and Doune near Stirling, rebuilt for Robert Stewart, Duke of Albany in the fourteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Gunpowder weaponry fundamentally altered the nature of castle architecture, with existing castles being adapted to allow the use of gunpowder weapons by the incorporation of "keyhole" gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls being adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Ravenscraig, Kirkcaldy, begun about 1460, is probably the first castle in the British Isles to be built as an artillery fort, incorporating "D-shape" bastions that would better resist cannon fire and on which artillery could be mounted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The largest number of late medieval fortifications in Scotland built by nobles, about 800, were of the tower house design.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Smaller versions of tower houses in southern Scotland were known as peel towers, or pele houses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The defences of tower houses were primarily aimed to provide protection against smaller raiding parties and were not intended to put up significant opposition to an organised military assault, leading historian Stuart Reid to characterise them as "defensible rather than defensive".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were typically a tall, square, stone-built, crenelated building; often also surrounded by a barmkin or bawn, a walled courtyard designed to hold valuable animals securely, but not necessarily intended for serious defence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] They were built extensively on both sides of the border with England, and James IV's forfeiture of the Lordship of the Isles in 1494 led to an immediate burst of tower building across the region.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The extensive building and rebuilding of royal palaces in the Renaissance style probably began under James III and accelerated under James IV.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] These works have been seen as directly reflecting the influence of Renaissance styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Linlithgow was first constructed under James I, under the direction of master of work John de Waltoun, and was referred to as a palace, apparently the first use of this term in the country, from 1429.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] This was extended under James III and began to correspond to a fashionable quadrangular, corner-towered Italian signorial palace of a *palatium ad modem castri* (a castle-style palace), combining classical symmetry with neo-chivalric imagery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] There is evidence of Italian masons working for James IV, in whose reign Linlithgow was completed, and other palaces were rebuilt with Italianate proportions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] Scotland is known for its dramatically placed castles and towers, which have become an accepted part of a romantic landscape.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] The Reformation in the mid-sixteenth century would lead to the rejection of many features of Medieval churches, resulting in the widespread destruction of Medieval church furnishings, ornaments and decoration, and would usher in new architectural forms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/architecture-of-scotland-in-the-middle-ages] However, they would be revived from the 1850s to the 1890s, when large Gothic revival churches were built in considerable numbers for all the major denominations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the early Middle Ages, there were distinct material cultures evident in the different federations and kingdoms within what is now Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Pictish art was the only uniquely Scottish medieval style; it can be seen in the extensive survival of carved stones, particularly in the north and east of the country, which hold a variety of recurring images and patterns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It can also be seen in elaborate metal work that largely survives in buried hoards.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Irish-Scots art from the kingdom of Dál Riata suggests that it was one of the places, as a crossroads between cultures, where the Insular style developed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Insular art is the name given to the common style that developed in Britain and Ireland from the eighth century and which became highly influential in continental Europe and contributed to the development of Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Scotland adopted the Romanesque style relatively late and retained and revived elements of its style after the Gothic style had become dominant from the thirteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much of the best Scottish artwork of the High and Late Middle Ages was either religious in nature or realised in metal and woodwork, and has not survived the impact of time and the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] However, examples of sculpture are extant as part of church architecture, including evidence of elaborate church interiors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From the thirteenth century there are relatively large numbers of monumental effigies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Native craftsmanship can be seen in a variety of items.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Visual illustration can be seen in the illumination of charters and occasional survivals of church paintings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving copies of individual portraits are relatively crude, but more impressive are the works or artists commissioned from the continent, particularly the Netherlands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] About 250 Pictish stones survive and have been assigned by scholars to three classes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class I stones are those thought to date to the period up to the seventh century and are the most numerous group.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The stones are largely unshaped and include incised symbols of animals such as fish and the Pictish beast, everyday objects such as mirrors, combs and tuning forks and abstract symbols defined by names including V-rod, double disc and Z-rod.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are found between from the Firth of Forth to Shetland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The greatest concentrations are in Sutherland, around modern Inverness and Aberdeen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Good examples include the Dunrobin (Sutherland) and Aberlemno stones (Angus).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class II stones are carefully shaped slabs dating after the arrival of Christianity in the eighth and ninth centuries, with a cross on one face and a wide range of symbols on the reverse.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In smaller numbers than Class I stones, they predominate in southern Pictland, in Perth, Angus and Fife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Good examples include Glamis 2, which contains a finely executed Celtic cross on the main face with two opposing male figures, a centaur, cauldron, deer head and a triple disc symbol and Cossans, Angus, which shows a high-prowed Pictish boat with oarsmen and a figure facing forward in the prow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Class III stones are thought to overlap chronologically with Class II stones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Most are elaborately shaped and incised cross-slabs, some with figurative scenes, but lacking idiomatic Pictish symbols.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are widely distributed but predominate in the southern Pictish areas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Items of metalwork have been found throughout Pictland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The earlier Picts appear to have had a considerable amount of silver available, probably from raiding further south, or the payment of subsidies to keep them from doing so.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The very large hoard of late Roman hacksilver found at Traprain Law may have originated in either way.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The largest hoard of early Pictish metalwork was found in 1819 at Norrie's Law in Fife, but unfortunately much was dispersed and melted down.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Over ten heavy silver chains, some over 0.5 metres (1.6 ft) long, have been found from this period; the double-linked Whitecleuch Chain is one of only two that have a penannular ring, with symbol decoration including enamel, which shows how these were probably used as "choker" necklaces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The St Ninian's Isle Treasure of 28 silver and silver-gilt objects, contains perhaps the best collection of late Pictish forms, from the Christian period, when Pictish metalwork style, as with stone-carving, gradually merged with Insular, Anglo-Saxon and Viking styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Thomas Charles-Edwards has suggested that the kingdom of Dál Riata was a cross-roads between the artistic styles of the Picts and those of Ireland, with which the Scots settlers in what is now Argyll kept close contacts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] This can be seen in representations found in excavations of the fortress of Dunadd, which combine Pictish and Irish elements.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] This included extensive evidence for the production of high status jewellery and moulds from the seventh century that indicate the production of pieces similar to the Hunterston brooch, found in Ayrshire, which may have been made in Dál Riata, but with elements that suggest Irish origins.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These and other finds, including a trumpet spiral decorated hanging bowl disc and a stamped animal decoration (or pressblech), perhaps from a bucket or drinking horn, indicate the ways in which Dál Riata was one of the locations where the Insular style was developed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the eighth and ninth centuries the Pictish elite adopted true penannular brooches with lobed terminals from Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Some older Irish pseudo-penannular brooches were adapted to the Pictish style, for example the Breadalbane Brooch (British Museum).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The eighth century Monymusk Reliquary has elements of Pictish and Irish style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is only one known pagan burial in Scotland, at Dalmeny Midlothian, which contains a necklace of beads similar to those found in mid-seventh-century southern England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Other isolated finds include a gold object from Dalmeny, shaped like a truncated pyramid, with filigree and garnet, similar to sword harness mounts found at Sutton Hoo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is also a bun-shaped loom from Yetholm, Roxburghshire and a ring with an Anglian runic inscription.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From eastern Scotland there is a seventh-century sword pommel from Culbin Sands, Moray and the Burghead drinking horn mount.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] After Christianisation in the seventh century artistic styles in Northumbria, which then reached to the Firth of Forth, interacted with those in Ireland and what is now Scotland to become part of the common style historians have identified as Insular or Hiberno-Saxon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Insular art, or Hiberno-Saxon art, is the name given to the common style produced in Scotland, Britain and Anglo-Saxon England from the seventh century, with the combining of Celtic and Anglo-Saxon forms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving examples of Insular art are found in metalwork, carving, but mainly in illuminated manuscripts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In manuscripts surfaces are highly decorated with intricate patterning, with no attempt to give an impression of depth, volume or recession.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The best examples include the Book of Kells, which may have been wholly or partly created in Iona, and the Book of Durrow, which may be from Ireland or Northumbria.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Carpet pages are a characteristic feature of Insular manuscripts, although historiated initials (an Insular invention), canon tables and figurative miniatures, especially Evangelist portraits, are also common.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The finest era of the style was brought to an end by the disruption to monastic centres and aristocratic life of the Viking raids in the late eighth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Christianity discouraged the burial of grave goods so the majority of examples of insular metalwork that survive from the Christian period have been found in archaeological contexts that suggest they were rapidly hidden, lost or abandoned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There are a few exceptions, notably portable shrines ("cumdachs") for books or relics, several of which have been continuously owned, mostly by churches on the Continent—though the Monymusk Reliquary has always been in Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The highest quality survivals are either secular jewellery, the largest and most elaborate pieces probably for male wearers, tableware or altarware.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The finest church pieces were probably made by secular workshops, often attached to a royal household, though other pieces were made by monastic workshops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There are a number of large brooches, each of their designs is wholly individual in detail, and the workmanship is varied.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Many elements of the designs can be directly related to elements used in manuscripts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Surviving stones used in decoration are semi-precious ones, with amber and rock crystal among the commonest, and some garnets.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Coloured glass, enamel and millefiori glass, probably imported, are also used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] None of the major insular manuscripts, like the Book of Kells, have preserved their elaborate jewelled metal covers, but documentary evidence indicates that these were as spectacular as the few remaining continental examples.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The most significant survivals in sculpture are in High crosses, large free-standing stone crosses, usually carved in relief with patterns, biblical iconography and occasionally inscriptions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The tradition may have begun in Ireland or Anglo-Saxon England and then spread to Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They are found throughout the British Isles and often feature a stone ring around the intersection, forming a Celtic cross, apparently an innovation of Celtic Christianity, that may have begun at Iona.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Distribution in Scotland is heaviest in the Highlands and Islands and they can be dated to the period c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] All the surviving crosses are of stone, but there are indications that large numbers of wooden crosses may also have existed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In Scotland biblical iconography is less common than in Ireland, but the subject of King David is relatively frequently depicted.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In the east the influence of Pictish sculpture can be seen, in areas of Viking occupation and settlement, crosses for the tenth to the twelfth centuries have distinctive Scandinavian patterns, often mixed with native styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Important examples dated to the eighth century include St Martin's Cross on Iona, the Kildalton Cross from the Hebrides and the Anglo-Saxon Ruthwell Cross.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Through the Hiberno-Scottish mission to the continent, insular art was highly influential on subsequent European Medieval art, especially the decorative elements of Romanesque and Gothic styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Viking art avoided naturalism, favouring stylised animal motifs to create its ornamental patterns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Ribbon-interlace was important and plant motifs became fashionable in the tenth and eleventh centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Most Scottish artefacts come from 130 "pagan" burials in the north and west from the mid-ninth to the mid-tenth centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These include jewellery, weapons and occasional elaborate high status items.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Amongst the most impressive of these is the Scar boat burial, on Orkney, which contained an elaborate sword, quiver with arrows, a brooch, bone comb, gaming pieces and the Scar Dragon Plaque, made from whalebone, most of which were probably made in Scandinavia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] From the west, another boat burial at Kiloron Bay in Colonsay revealed a sword, shield, iron cauldron and enamelled scales, which may be Celtic in origin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] A combination of Viking and Celtic styles can be seen in a penannular brooch from Pierowall in Orkney, which has a Pictish-style looped pin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is about two inches in diameter, with traces of gilding, and probably housed a piece of amber surrounded by interweaving ribbons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] After the conversion to Christianity, from the tenth to the twelfth centuries, stone crosses and cross-slabs in Viking occupied areas of the Highlands and Islands were carved with successive styles of Viking ornament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They were frequently mixed with native interlace and animal patterns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Examples include the eleventh-century cross-slab from Dóid Mhàiri on the island of Islay, where the plant motifs on either side of the cross-shaft are based upon the Ringerike style of Viking art.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The most famous artistic find from modern Scotland, the Lewis Chessmen, from Uig, were probably made in Trondheim in Norway, but contain some decoration that may have been influenced by Celtic patterns.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much of the best Scottish artwork of the High and Late Middle Ages was either religious in nature or realised in metal and woodwork and has not survived the impact of time and the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] However, examples of sculpture are extant as part of church architecture, a small number of significant crafted items have also survived and, for the end of the period, there is evidence of painting, particularly the extensive commissioning of works in the Low Countries and France.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The interiors of churches were often more elaborate before the Reformation, with highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Deskford and Kinkell.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Monumental effigies began to appear in churches from the thirteenth century and they were usually fully coloured and gilded.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Many were founders and patrons of churches and chapels, including members of the clergy, knights and often their wives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] In contrast to England, where the fashion for stone-carved monuments gave way to brass etchings, they continued to be produced until the end of the Medieval period, with the largest group dating from the fifteenth century, including the very elaborate Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Sometimes the best continental artists were employed, as for Robert I's elaborate tomb in Dunfermline Abbey, which was made in his lifetime by the Parisian sculptor Thomas of Chartres, but of which only fragments now survive.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The greatest group of surviving sculpture from this period are from the West Highlands, beginning in the fourteenth century on Iona under the patronage of the Lordship of the Isles and continuing until the Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Common motifs were ships, swords, harps and Romanesque vine leaf tracery with Celtic elements.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Survivals from late Medieval church fittings and objects in Scotland are exceptionally rare even compared to those from comparable areas like England or Norway, probably because of the thoroughness of their destruction in the Scottish Reformation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Scottish elite and church now participated in a culture stretching across Europe, and many objects that do survive are imported, such as Limoges enamels.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is often difficult to decide the country of creation of others, as work in international styles was produced in Scotland, along with pieces retaining more distinctive local styles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Two secular small chests with carved whalebone panels and metal fittings illustrate some aspects of the Scottish arts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Eglington and Fife Caskets are very similar and were probably made by the same workshop around 1500, as boxes for valuables such as jewellery or documents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Key examples of native craftsmanship on items include the Bute mazer, the earliest surviving drinking cup of its type, made of maple-wood and with elaborate silver-gilt ornamentation, dated to around 1320.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Savernake Horn was probably made for the earl of Moray in the fourteenth century and looted by the English in the mid-sixteenth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] A few significant reliquaries survive from West Scotland, examples of the habit of the Celtic church of treating the possessions rather than the bones of saints as relics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] As in Irish examples these were partly reworked and elaborated at intervals over a long period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] These are St Fillan's Crozier and its "Coigreach" or reliquary, between them with elements from each century from the eleventh to the fifteenth, the Guthrie Bell Shrine, Iona, twelfth to fifteenth century, and the Kilmichael Glassary Bell Shrine, Argyll, mid-twelfth century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] The Skye Chess piece is a single elaborate piece in carved walrus ivory, with two warriors carrying heraldic shields in a framework of openwork vegetation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] It is thought to be Scottish, of the mid-thirteenth century, with aspects similar to both English and Norwegian pieces.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] They would be made compulsory for barons of the king in a statute of 1401 and seal matrices show very high standards of skill and artistry.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Examples of items that were probably the work of continental artists include the delicate hanging lamp in St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] John's Kirk in Perth, the vestments and hangings in Holyrood and the Medieval maces of the Universities of St Andrews and Glasgow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Manuscript illumination continued into the late Middle Ages, moving from elaborate gospels to charters, like that confirming the rights of Kelso Abbey from 1159.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Very little painting from Scottish churches survives.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] There is only one surviving Doom painting in Scotland, at Guthrie near Arbroath, which may have been painted by the same artist as the elaborate crucifixion and other paintings at Foulis Easter, eighteen miles away.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] As in England, the monarchy may have had model portraits of royalty used for copies and reproductions, but the versions of native royal portraits that survive are generally crude by continental standards.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/art-in-medieval-scotland] Much more impressive are the works or artists imported from the continent, particularly the Netherlands, generally considered the centre of painting in the Northern Renaissance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The term originates from the Latin term *barō*, via Old French.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The use of the title *baron* came to England via the Norman Conquest of 1066, then the Normans brought the title to Scotland and Southern Italy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] It later spread to Scandinavian and Slavic lands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The word *baron* comes from the Old French *baron*, from a Late Latin *barō* "man; servant, soldier, mercenary" (so used in Salic law; Alemannic law has *barus* in the same sense).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The scholar Isidore of Seville in the 7th century thought the word was from Greek βᾰρῠ́ς "heavy" (because of the "heavy work" done by mercenaries), but the word is presumably of Old Frankish origin, cognate with Old English *beorn* meaning "warrior, nobleman".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Cornutus in the first century already reports a word *barones* which he took to be of Gaulish origin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the Peerage of England, the Peerage of Great Britain, the Peerage of Ireland and the Peerage of the United Kingdom (but not in the Peerage of Scotland), barons form the lowest rank, placed immediately below viscounts.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] A woman of baronial rank has the title **baroness**.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] After the Norman Conquest in 1066, the Norman dynasty introduced an adaptation of the French feudal system to the Kingdom of England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Initially, the term "baron" on its own was not a title or rank, but the "barons of the King" were the men of the king.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Previously, in the Anglo-Saxon kingdom of England, the king's companions held the title of earl and in Scotland, the title of thane.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] All who held their feudal barony "in-chief of the king", that is with the king as his immediate overlord, became alike *barones regis* ("barons of the king"), bound to perform a stipulated annual military service and obliged to attend his council.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Initially those who held land directly from the king by military service, from earls downwards, all bore alike the title of baron, which was thus the factor uniting all members of the ancient baronage as peers one of another.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Under King Henry II, the *Dialogus de Scaccario* already distinguished between greater barons, who held *per baroniam* by knight's service, and lesser barons, who held manors.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Thus in this historical sense, lords of manors are barons, or freemen; however they are not entitled to be styled as such.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] John Selden writes in *Titles of Honour*, "The word *Baro* (Latin for 'baron') hath been also so much communicated, that not only all Lords of Mannors have been from ancient time, and are at this day called sometimes Barons (as in the stile of their Court Barons, which is *Curia Baronis, &c*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] These representatives developed into the knights of the shire, elected by the county court presided over by the sheriff, who themselves formed the precursor of the House of Commons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Thus appeared a definite distinction, which eventually had the effect of restricting to the greater barons alone the privileges and duties of peerage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Later, the king started to create new baronies in one of two ways: by a writ of summons directing a chosen man to attend Parliament, and in an even later development by letters patent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Writs of summons became the normal method in medieval times, displacing the method of feudal barony, but creation of baronies by letters patent is the sole method adopted in modern times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Since the adoption of summons by writ, baronies thus no longer relate directly to land-holding, and thus no more feudal baronies needed to be created from then on.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Following the *Modus Tenendi Parliamenta* of 1419, the Tenures Abolition Act 1660, the Feudal Tenure Act 1662, and the Fines and Recoveries Act 1834, titles of feudal barony became obsolete and without legal force.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The Tenures Abolition Act 1660 specifically states: baronies by tenure were converted into baronies by writ.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The rest ceased to exist as feudal baronies by tenure, becoming baronies in free socage, that is to say under a "free" (hereditable) contract requiring payment of monetary rents.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the 20th century, Britain introduced the concept of non-hereditary life peers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] All appointees to this distinction have, except for the Duke of Edinburgh, been at the rank of baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In accordance with the tradition applied to hereditary peers, they too are formally addressed in parliament by their peers as "The Noble Lord".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In addition, baronies are often used by their holders as subsidiary titles, for example as courtesy titles for the son and heir of an Earl or higher-ranked peer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The Scottish baronial title tends to be used when a landed family is not in possession of any United Kingdom peerage title of higher rank, subsequently granted, or has been created a knight of the realm.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Several members of the royal family with the style of *Royal Highness* are also titled Barons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] For example, William, Prince of Wales is also The Baron of Renfrew and The Baron Carrickfergus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Some non-royal Barons are related to the royal family; for example, Maurice Roche, 6th Baron Fermoy is William's first cousin once removed, through William's late mother, Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the 4th Baron Fermoy's granddaughter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The title of baron (Irish: *barún*) was created in the Peerage of Ireland shortly after the Norman invasion of Ireland (1169).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Ireland's first baronies included Baron Athenry (1172), Baron Offaly (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] A person holding a peerage in the rank of baron is entitled to a coronet bearing six pearls around the rim, equally spaced and all of equal size and height.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The rim itself is neither jewelled nor "chased" (which is the case for the coronets of peers of higher degree).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The actual coronet is worn only for the coronation of a new monarch, but a baron can bear his coronet of rank on his coat of arms above the shield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In heraldry, the baron's coronet is shown with four of the balls visible.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Formally, barons are styled *The Right Honourable The Lord [Barony]* and barons’ wives are styled *The Right Honourable The Lady [Barony]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Baronesses in their own right, whether hereditary or for life, are either styled *The Right Honourable The Baroness [Barony]* or *The Right Honourable The Lady [Barony]*, mainly based on personal preference (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Lady Thatcher and Baroness Warsi, both life baronesses in their own right).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Less formally, one refers to or addresses a baron as *Lord [Barony]* and his wife as *Lady [Barony]*, and baronesses in their own right as *Baroness [X]* or *Lady [X]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In direct address, barons and baronesses can also be referred to as *My Lord*, *Your Lordship*, or *Your Ladyship or My Lady*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The husband of a baroness in her own right gains no title or style from his wife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Children of barons and baronesses in their own right, whether hereditary or for life, have the style *The Honourable [Forename] [Surname]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] After the death of the father or mother, the child may continue to use this style.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Courtesy barons are styled *Lord [Barony]*, and their wives *Lady [Barony]*; the article "The" is always absent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] If the courtesy baron is not a Privy Counsellor, the style *The Right Honourable* will also be absent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] It is very common for the surnames of barons and baronesses to be identical to or included in the formal title of their barony.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] However, when addressed as a peer, the title of *Lord*, *Lady*, or *Baroness* is followed by the name of his or her barony, not his personal name.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This is relevant when a baron or baroness's title is completely different from his or her personal surname (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] William Thomson, Lord Kelvin) or includes a territorial designation in addition to his surname (e.g.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This also means that including a baron or baroness's forename before his or her title is incorrect and potentially misleading.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] For example, "Lady Margaret Thatcher" (as opposed to "Lady Thatcher") would imply that she was the daughter of an earl, marquess, or duke, or Lady of the Garter or Thistle not holding a peerage rather than a baroness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Likewise, in the case of men, "Lord Digby Jones" (as opposed to "Lord Jones of Birmingham") would imply that he was the younger son of a marquess or duke rather than a baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The United Kingdom has a policy of including titles of nobility on passports: the title is entered into the surname field and a standard observation is recorded giving the holder's full name and title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] A Baron would therefore record his surname as *Lord [Barony]*, and the observation would note that *The holder is The Right Honourable [given names] [surname] Lord [Barony]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] However, if the title of an applicant's peerage is different from his surname, he can choose whether to use his surname or title in the surname field.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] A baroness in her own right would substitute "Baroness" for "Lord", and the wife of a Baron would similarly substitute "Lady".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Titles of nobility are checked against Debrett's Peerage, Who's Who, or The London Gazette by the passport office on application.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Scotland, the rank of baron is a rank of the ancient nobility of the Baronage of Scotland and refers to the holder of a barony, formerly a feudal superiority or prescriptive barony attached to land erected into a free barony by Crown Charter.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The Court of the Lord Lyon will officially recognise those possessing the dignity of baron on petition who meet certain criteria, and will grant them baronial arms with a helmet befitting their degree.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Scottish barons rank below Lords of Parliament and while noble have the status of minor baron, being a non-Peerage rank; as such it can be transferred by either inheritance or assignation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Sir Thomas Innes of Learney, in his *Scots Heraldry* (2nd Ed., p.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] 88, note 1), states that "The Act 1672, cap 47, specially qualifies the degrees thus: Nobles (i.e. peers, the term being here used in a restricted seventeenth-century English sense), Barons (i.e.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Lairds of baronial fiefs and their 'heirs', who, even if fiefless, are equivalent to heads of Continental baronial houses) and Gentlemen (apparently all other armigers)." Baronets and knights are evidently classed as 'Gentlemen' here and are of a lower degree than Barons.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The Scottish equivalent of an English baron is a Lord of Parliament.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Scottish barons were entitled to a red cap of maintenance (chapeau) turned up ermine if petitioning for a grant or matriculation of a coat of arms between the 1930s and 2004.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This chapeau is identical to the red cap worn by an English baron, but without the silver balls or gilt.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This is sometimes depicted in armorial paintings between the shield and the helmet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Additionally, if the baron is the head of a family, he may include a chiefly coronet which is similar to a ducal coronet, but with four strawberry leaves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Because the chapeau was a relatively recent innovation, a number of ancient arms of Scottish feudal barons do not display the chapeau.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Now, Scottish barons are principally recognised by the baron's helm, which in Scotland is a steel helmet with grille of three grilles, garnished in gold.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Occasionally, the great tilting-helm garnished with gold is shown, or a helmet befitting a higher rank, if held.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Scottish barons style their surnames similarly to Clan Chiefs if they own the caput, with the name of their barony following their name, as in *John Smith of Edinburgh, Baron of Edinburgh* otherwise *John Smith, Baron of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Most formally, and in writing, they are styled as *The Much Honoured Baron of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Their wives are styled *Lady Edinburgh*, or *The Baroness of Edinburgh*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The phrase *Lady of Edinburgh* is wrong if the lady in question does not hold a Scottish barony in her own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Orally, Scottish barons may be addressed with the name of their barony, as in *Edinburgh* or else as *Baron* without anything else following, which if present would suggest a peerage barony.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Informally, when referring to a Scots baron in the third person, the name *Baron of [X]* is used or simply *[X]*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] During the Ancien Régime, French baronies were very much like Scottish ones.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Feudal landholders who possessed a barony were entitled to style themselves as a baron (French: *baron*) if they were nobles; a *roturier* (commoner) could only be a *seigneur de la baronnie* (lord of the barony).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] French baronies could be sold freely until 1789, when the Constituent Assembly abolished feudal law.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The title of baron was assumed as a *titre de courtoisie* by many nobles, whether members of the Nobles of the Robe or cadets of Nobles of the Sword who held no title in their own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] 1804–1815) created a new imperial nobility in which *baron* appeared from 1808 as the second-lowest title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The titles were inherited through a male-only line of descent and could not be purchased.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In 1815, King Louis XVIII created a new peerage system and a Chamber of Peers, based on the British model.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Baron-peer was the lowest title, but the heirs to pre-1789 barons could remain barons, as could the elder sons of viscount-peers and the younger sons of count-peers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This peerage system was abolished in 1848.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The wife of a *Freiherr* (Baron) is called a *Freifrau* or sometimes *Baronin*, his daughter *Freiin* or sometimes *Baroness*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Families which had always held this status were called *Uradel* ('primordial/ancient/original nobility'), and were heraldically entitled to a three-pointed coronet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Families which had been ennobled at a definite point in time (*Briefadel* or "nobility by patent") had seven points on their coronet.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] These families held their fief in vassalage from a suzerain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The holder of an allodial (i.e. suzerain-free) barony was thus called a Free Lord, or *Freiherr*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Subsequently, sovereigns in Germany conferred the title of *Freiherr* as a rank in the nobility, without implication of allodial or feudal status.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Since 1919, hereditary titles have had no legal status in Germany.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In modern, republican Germany, *Freiherr* and *Baron* remain heritable only as part of the legal surname (and may thereby be transmitted to husbands, wives and children, without implication of nobility).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Austria, hereditary titles have been completely banned.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Thus, a member of the formerly reigning House of Habsburg or members of the former nobility would in most cases simply be addressed as *Herr/Frau (Habsburg)* in an official/public context, for instance in the media.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Still, in both countries, honorary styles like "His/Her (Imperial/Royal) Highness", "Serenity", etc. persist in social use as a form of courtesy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Generally, all legitimate males of a German baronial family inherit the title *Freiherr* or *Baron* from birth, as all legitimate daughters inherit the title of *Freiin* or *Baroness*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] As a result, German barons have been more numerous than those of such countries where primogeniture with respect to title inheritance prevails (or prevailed), such as France and the United Kingdom.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Italy, *barone* was the lowest rank of feudal nobility except for that of *signore* or *vassallo* (lord of the manor).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The title of baron was most generally introduced into southern Italy (including Sicily) by the Normans during the 11th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Whereas originally a barony might consist of two or more manors, by 1700 we see what were formerly single manors erected into baronies, counties or even marquisates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Since the early 1800s, when feudalism was abolished in the various Italian states, it has often been granted as a simple hereditary title without any territorial designation or *predicato*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The untitled younger son of a baron is a *nobile dei baroni* and in informal usage might be called a baron, while certain baronies devolve to heirs male general.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Since 1948 titles of nobility have not been recognised by the Italian state.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the absence of a nobiliary or heraldic authority in Italy there are, in fact, numerous persons who claim to be barons or counts without any basis for such claims.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Baron and noble (*nobile*) are hereditary titles and, as such, could only be created or recognised by the kings of Italy or (before 1860) the pre-unitary Italian states such as the Two Sicilies, Tuscany, Parma or Modena, or by the Holy See (Vatican) or the Republic of San Marino.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Beginning around 1800, a number of *signori* (lords of the manor) began to style themselves *barone* but in many cases this was not sanctioned legally by decree, while there was even less justification in the holder of any large (non-feudal) landed estate calling himself a baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Nevertheless, both were common practices.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In most of peninsular Italy the widespread medieval introduction of the title was Longobardic, while in Sicily and Sardinia it was coeval with Norman rule some centuries later, and one referred to the *baronage* when speaking of landed nobles generally.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The heraldic coronet of an Italian baron is a jewelled rim of gold surmounted by seven visible pearls, set upon the rim directly or upon stems; alternately, the French style coronet (entwined in a string of small pearls, with or without four bigger visible pearls set upon the rim) is used.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the medieval era, some allodial and enfeoffed lands held by nobles were created or recognised as baronies by the Holy Roman Emperors, within whose realm most of the Low Countries lay.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Subsequently, the Habsburgs continued to confer the baronial title in the Southern Netherlands, first as kings of Spain and then, again, as emperors until abolition of the Holy Roman Empire, but these had become titular elevations rather than grants of new territory.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the Netherlands after 1815, titles of baron (Dutch: *baron* (m), *barones* (f)) authorised by previous monarchs (except those of the Napoleonic Kingdom of Holland) were usually recognised by the Dutch kings.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] But such recognition was not automatic, having to be authenticated by the Supreme Council of Nobility and then approved by the sovereign.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This ceased to be possible after the Dutch constitution was revised in 1983.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] More than one hundred Dutch baronial families have been recognised.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The title is usually inherited by all males descended patrilineally from the original recipient of the title, although in a few noble families *baron* is the title of cadet family members, whilst in a few others it is heritable according to primogeniture.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] After its secession in 1830, Belgium incorporated into its nobility all titles of baron borne by Belgian citizens, which had been recognised by the Netherlands since 1815.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In addition, its monarchs have since created or recognised other titles of baron, and the sovereign continues to exercise the prerogative to confer baronial and other titles of nobility.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] *Baron* is the third lowest title within the nobility system above knight (French: *chevalier*, Dutch: *ridder*) and below *viscount*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] There are still a number of families in Belgium that bear the title of baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Luxembourg's monarch retains the right to confer the baronial title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Two of the grand duchy's prime ministers inherited baronial titles that were used during their tenures in office, Victor de Tornaco and Félix de Blochausen.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Norway, king Magnus VI of Norway (1238–1280) replaced the title Lendmann with Baron, but in 1308 Haakon V abolished the title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The present corresponding title is *baron* in the Danish nobility and the Norwegian nobility, *friherre* in the Swedish nobility (*baron* is used orally, while it is written as *friherre*), and *vapaaherra* in the nobility of Finland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the beginning, Finnish nobles were all without honorific titulature, and known simply as lords.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Since the Middle Ages, each head of a noble family had been entitled to a vote in any of Finland's provincial diets whenever held, as in the realm's House of Nobility of the Riksdag of the Estates.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In 1561, Sweden's King Eric XIV granted the hereditary titles of count and *vapaaherra* to some of these, but not all.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Although their cadet family members were not entitled to vote or sit in the Riksdag, they were legally entitled to the same title as the head of the family, but in customary address they became *Paroni* or *Paronitar*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Theoretically, in the 16th and 17th centuries, families elevated to *vapaaherra* status were granted a barony in fief, enjoying some rights of taxation and judicial authority.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Subsequently, the "barony" was titular, usually attached to a family property, which was sometimes entailed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Their exemptions from taxes on landed properties continued into the 20th century, although in the 19th century tax reforms narrowed this privilege.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Nobility creations continued until 1917, the end of Finland's grand ducal monarchy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Muscovite Russia had no traditional baronial titles of its own; they were introduced in early Imperial Russia by Peter the Great.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the hierarchy of nobility introduced by Peter the Great, barons (барон) ranked above untitled nobility and below counts (граф, *graf*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The styles "Your Well-born" (Ваше благородие, *Vashe blagorodiye*) and "Master Baron" (Господин барон, *Gospodin baron*) were used to address a Russian baron.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] There were two main groups of nobility which held the baronial title.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] One was the Baltic German nobility, for which Russia merely recognised their pre-existing titles; the other was new barons created by the Emperors of Russia after 1721.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Like in many other countries, new baronial titles were often created by ennoblement of rich bourgeoisie.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The title of baron, along with the rest of the noble hierarchy, was abolished in December 1917 after the Bolshevik Revolution; however, certain leaders of the White movement like Baron Pyotr Wrangel and Roman von Ungern-Sternberg continued to use the title until the end of the Russian Civil War.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Spain, the title follows *Vizconde* in the noble hierarchy, and ranks above *Señor*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] *Baronesa* is the feminine form, for the wife of a baron or for a woman who has been granted the title in her own right.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In general, titles of *baron* created before the 19th century originate from the Crown of Aragon.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] *Barons* lost territorial jurisdiction around the middle of the 19th century, and from then on the title became purely honorific.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Although most *barons* have not held the rank of *grandeza* as well, the title has been conferred in conjunction with the *grandeza*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] The sovereign continues to grant baronial titles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Like other major Western noble titles, *baron* is sometimes used to render certain titles in non-Western languages with their own traditions, even though they are necessarily historically unrelated and thus hard to compare, which are considered 'equivalent' in relative rank.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] This is the case with China's *nanjue* (*nan-chueh*) (Chinese: 男爵), hereditary title of nobility of the fifth rank, as well as its derivatives and adaptations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In some *republics* of continental Europe, the unofficial title of "Baron" retains a purely social prestige, with no particular political privileges.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Armenian, the word "Baron" should not be confused with the similar word "Paron" (Armenian: Պարոն), which is a title given to ordinary men, equivalent to 'Sir' or 'Mr'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In Latvian, the term used by the Baltic German nobility is *barons* (female: *baronese*), although since the 19th century b*rīvkungs* (*brīvkundze*), a translation of Freiherr began to gain popularity.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] In the Polynesian island monarchy of Tonga, as opposed to the situation in Europe, barons are granted this imported title (in English), alongside traditional chiefly styles, and continue to hold and exercise some political power.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] Barons and baronesses have appeared in various works of fiction.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/baron] For examples of fictional barons and baronesses, see List of fictional nobility#Barons and baronesses.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Bere is a landrace adapted to growing on soils with a low pH (acidic) and to a short growing season with long hours of daylight, as found in the high latitudes of northern Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It is sown in the spring and harvested in the summer.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Because of its very rapid growth rate, it is sown late but is often the first crop to be harvested.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It is known locally as *the 90-day barley*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Originally *bere* or *beir* or *bear* is a generic Scots word for barley of any kind, from Old English *bere*, "barley", and was used throughout the country.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Now it is used mainly in the north of Scotland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It often referred to barley of a lower yield, and the phrase "bear meal marriage" usually meant one that would not bring much wealth with it.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Talking of the wide variety of crops in England, and crop rotation, Professor T.C.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Smout writes: "In Scotland, there is no evidence of such variation possibly because the range of crops was so much smaller — often only oats or bear (a primitive form of barley)".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Bere is a very old grain that may have been grown in Britain since Neolithic times.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Another early term for it was "bygge" or "big", probably originating from *bygg*, the Old Norse term for barley.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It became well-adapted to the far north of Britain as successive generations of farmers grew it, selecting each year's seeds from the best plants of the previous year.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] In the 19th and early 20th centuries, bere was an important crop in the Highlands and Islands region of Scotland, providing grain for milling and malting and straw for thatching and animal bedding.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It was also exported from Orkney and other ports in Scotland to Northern Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] The advent of higher-yielding barley varieties led to a deep decline in bere growing during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] It survives in cultivation today thanks to Barony Mills, a 19th-century watermill, which purchases the grain to produce *beremeal* which is used locally in bread, biscuits, and the traditional beremeal bannock.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] The Agronomy Institute at Orkney College UHI in Scotland has had a research programme on Bere since 2002.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] The programme is aimed at developing new markets for the crop and developing best practices for growing it more easily and with increased yield.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] As a result of this research, several new markets (whisky, beer and biscuits) have been developed for Orkney Bere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] The crop is also being grown on the island of Islay, for whisky production by Bruichladdich Distillery.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Bere flour has quite high levels of folate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Bere has a long history of use in making alcoholic beverages.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] Historical accounts from the 15th century onward show that Orkney produced large amounts of malt and beer, most of it probably from bere.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] An ancient tradition of making bere-based homebrew survives until this day in the islands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] During the 19th century, the Campbeltown distilleries used large quantities of bere in making Scotch whisky.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bere-grain] In the early 21st century some distillers began experimenting again with bere, and in 2006, the UK's most northern brewery released a bere-based microbrew.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The Anglian territory of Bernicia was approximately equivalent to the modern English counties of Northumberland, Tyne and Wear, and Durham, as well as the Scottish counties of Berwickshire and East Lothian, stretching from the Forth to the Tees.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] In the early 7th century, it merged with its southern neighbour, Deira, to form the kingdom of Northumbria, and its borders subsequently expanded considerably.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The Old English name *Beornice* is the tribal name, translated as 'Bernicians'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The name of the kingdom, *Beornica rice*, means 'Realm of the Bernicians'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Bernicia occurs in Old Welsh poetry as *Bryneich* or *Byrneich* and in the 9th-century *Historia Brittonum*, (§ 61) as *Berneich*, *Birneich*, *Bernech* and *Birnech*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Academics agree the name was originally Celtic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] This name was then adopted by the Anglian settlers who rendered it in Old English as *Bernice* (Northumbrian dialect) or *Beornice* (West Saxon dialect).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The counter hypothesis suggesting these names represent a Brythonic adaption of an earlier English form is considered less probable.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Local linguistic evidence suggests continued political activity in the area from the time of the Roman retreat from Britain and before the arrival of the Angles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Analysis of a potential derivation has not produced a consensus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The most commonly cited etymology gives the meaning as "Land of the Mountain Passes" or "Land of the Gaps" (tentatively proposed by Kenneth H.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] An earlier derivation from the tribal name of the Brigantes has been dismissed as linguistically unsound.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Koch suggested the conflation of a probable primary form **Bernech* with the native form **Brïγent* for the old *civitas Brigantum* as a result of Anglian expansion in that territory during the 7th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The Brythonic kingdom of the area was formed from what had once been the southern lands of the Votadini, possibly as part of the division of a supposed 'great northern realm' of Coel Hen in c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] This northern realm is referred to by Welsh scholars as *Yr Hen Ogledd* or, literally, "The Old North".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The kingdom may have been ruled from the site that later became the English Bamburgh, which certainly features in Welsh sources as *Din Guardi*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Near this high-status residence lay the island of Lindisfarne (formerly known, in Welsh, as *Ynys Medcaut*), which became the seat of the Bernician bishops.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] It is unknown when the Angles finally conquered the whole region, but around 604 is likely.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] There are several Old Welsh pedigrees of princely "Men of the North" (*Gwŷr y Gogledd*) that may represent the kings of the British kingdom in the area, which may have been called *Bryneich*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] John Morris surmised that the line of a certain Morcant Bulc referred to these monarchs, chiefly because he identified this man as the murderer of Urien Rheged who was, at the time, besieging Lindisfarne.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Some of the Angles of Bernicia (Old English: *Beornice*) may have been employed as mercenaries along Hadrian's Wall during the late Roman period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Others are thought to have migrated north (by sea) from Deira in the early 6th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The first Anglian king in the historical record is Ida, who is said to have obtained the throne and the kingdom about 547.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] His sons spent many years fighting a united force from the surrounding Brythonic kingdoms until their alliance collapsed into civil war.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Ida's grandson, Æthelfrith (Æðelfriþ), united Deira with his own kingdom by force around 604.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] He ruled the two kingdoms (united as Northumbria) until he was defeated and killed by Rædwald of East Anglia (who had given refuge to Edwin, son of Ælle, king of Deira) around 616.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The early part of Edwin's reign was possibly spent fighting enemies from the Brythonic exiles of the old British kingdom, operating out of Gododdin.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] After this, it is said that on Easter Day 627 Edwin converted to Christianity in return for Elmet (a Cumbric-speaking kingdom that once existed in the modern-day West Riding of Yorkshire, near Leeds), joining the kingdom of Northumbria; which drew him into direct conflict with Wales proper.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Following the disastrous Battle of Hatfield Chase on 12 October 633, in which Edwin was defeated and killed by Cadwallon ap Cadfan of Gwynedd and Penda of Mercia, Northumbria was divided back into Bernicia and Deira.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Bernicia was then briefly ruled by Eanfrith, son of Æthelfrith, but after about a year he went to Cadwallon to sue for peace and was killed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Eanfrith's brother Oswald then raised an army and finally defeated Cadwallon at the Battle of Heavenfield in 634.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] After this victory, Oswald appears to have been recognised by both Bernicians and Deirans as king of a properly united Northumbria.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The kings of Bernicia were thereafter supreme in that kingdom, although Deira had its own sub-kings at times during the reigns of Oswiu and his son Ecgfrith.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] After the decisive defeat of Northumbrian forces by the Viking Great Heathen Army, at the Battle of York in 867, the united Kingdom of Northumbria disintegrated.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The lands north of the Tyne remained a de facto independent kingdom called Bamburgh after the stronghold of its high-reeves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] The lands between Tyne and Tees were granted to the Community of St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Cuthbert, forming an ecclesiastical buffer zone between Jórvík and Bamburgh.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] In 927 Ealdred accepted West Saxon overlordship; however, the lands north of the Tees remained outside of the West Saxon administrative system of shires and hundreds until after the Norman invasion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] In 973, Scots sovereignty over northern Bernicia, now known as Lothian, was acknowledged by Edgar of England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/bernicia] Under Oswald son of Æthelfrith, Bernicia was united with Deira to form Northumbria from 634 onward until the Viking invasion of the 9th Century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The **Black Death** was a plague pandemic that occurred in Europe from 1346 to 1353.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It was one of the most fatal pandemics in human history, leading to the death of up to 50 million people, or 50% of Europe's 14th-century population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The disease is caused by the bacterium *Yersinia pestis* and is spread by fleas and through the air.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] One of the most significant events in European history, the Black Death had far-reaching population, economic, and cultural effects.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It was the beginning of the second plague pandemic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The plague created religious, social, and economic upheavals, with profound effects on the course of European history.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Black Death was the second great natural disaster to strike Europe during the Late Middle Ages (the first one being the Great Famine of 1315–1317) and is estimated to have killed 30% to 60% of the European population, as well as approximately 33% of the population of the Middle East.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] There were further outbreaks throughout the Late Middle Ages and, also due to other contributing factors (the crisis of the late Middle Ages), the European population did not regain its 14th century level until the 16th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Outbreaks of the plague recurred around the world until the early 19th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The origin of the Black Death is disputed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Genetic analysis suggests *Yersinia pestis* bacteria evolved approximately 7,000 years ago, at the beginning of the Neolithic, with flea-mediated strains emerging around 3,800 years ago during the late Bronze Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The immediate territorial origins of the Black Death and its outbreak remain unclear, with some evidence pointing towards Central Asia, China, the Middle East, and Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The pandemic was reportedly first introduced to Europe during the siege of the Genoese trading port of Caffa in Crimea by the Golden Horde army of Jani Beg in 1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] From Crimea, it was most likely carried by fleas living on the black rats that travelled on Genoese ships, spreading through the Mediterranean Basin and reaching North Africa, West Asia, and the rest of Europe via Constantinople, Sicily, and the Italian Peninsula.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] There is evidence that once it came ashore, the Black Death mainly spread from person-to-person as pneumonic plague, thus explaining the quick inland spread of the epidemic, which was faster than would be expected if the primary vector was rat fleas causing bubonic plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] A 2026 study published in *Nature* identified the oldest known evidence of plague outbreaks in human remains, finding traces of Yersinia pestis DNA in the teeth of 18 ancient hunter-gatherers from four cemeteries near Lake Baikal in Siberia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Carbon dating revealed two outbreaks, with the earliest cases dating to approximately 5,500 years ago — some 200 years earlier than previously established.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Researchers concluded the disease likely spread initially from marmots through contact with raw organs or infected hides, and also transmitted between people through respiratory means.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Many victims were young children, with three young girls buried side by side among the dead.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] There has been a quest to find "patient zero", the earliest known victim(s) with evidence of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In 2022, in an article called "*The source of the Black Death in fourteenth-century central Eurasia*", researchers pointed to the earliest victims of the plague found at two cemeteries in the Chüy Valley near Lake Issyk-Kul in modern Kyrgyzstan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Here graves had tombstones with Syriac inscription, providing the name of the deceased, year of death and often the cause of death, showing a spike due to "pestilence" in 1338–1339.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The article reported DNA data to provide genetic evidence from the teeth of seven individuals from the two cemeteries at Kara-Djigach and Burana finding evidence of *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This confirms that the Yersinia pestis strain found in Kyrgyzstan predates and was the direct ancestor of the Black Death strains that devastated Europe and the Middle East starting in 1346–1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Mongol Empire, founded by Genghis Khan, reached its peak expansion between 1206 and 1279.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] By the time the Black Death emerged in Central Asia in the late 1330s, the Mongol Empire had already reached its maximum geographic extent and had fractured into four distinct khanates (the Golden Horde, the Ilkhanate, the Chagatai Khanate, and the Yuan Dynasty).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Black Death became a catalyst for the Mongol Empire's fall.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It disrupted trade as the Mongols relied on trade along the Silk Road and the plague spread along these trade routes, killing the merchants and officials who maintained the network.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] There was a depopulation of the ruling elite, decimating the Mongol administrative class in the Ilkhanate (Persia) and the Golden Horde (Russia), leading to political instability and the eventual overthrow of Mongol rulers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate served as the "Ground Zero" for the genetic ancestor of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] A 2022 research paper by Spyrou et al. identified the Yersinia pestis strain in the cemetery sites of Kara-Djigach and Tolyak in 1338–1339, which were located within the borders of the Chagatai Khanate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The discovery in this specific khanate changes the "origin story" of the Black Death from a vague Far Eastern source (China) to a specific Central Asian focal point.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate sits at the very root of the "four-way split" (diversification) of the plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This means the version that devastated the Ilkhanate, the Golden Horde, and Europe all radiated out from this single Central Asian source.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate was the geographic heart of the Silk Road.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It acted as the bridge between the Yuan Dynasty in the east and the Ilkhanate/Golden Horde in the west.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Because the Mongols maintained high-speed postal stations (Yam) and protected merchant caravans, they unintentionally created the perfect laboratory for a localized rodent-borne disease to become a transcontinental pandemic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Golden Horde played a pivotal role in the transmission of the Black Death from Central Asia to the Mediterranean.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In 1346, the plague reached the Horde's territories along the Volga River, devastating major urban centers like the capital Sarai.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The pandemic is famously associated with the Siege of Caffa (1346), where the Mongol army under Khan Jani Beg (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] 1342–1357) suffered heavy casualties from the disease while besieging the Genoese port.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Chroniclers like Gabriele de' Mussi recorded that the Mongols catapulted plague-infected corpses into the city, an early instance of biological warfare, which likely contributed to the escape of infected Genoese ships toward Sicily and Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The plague triggered a profound domestic collapse for the Golden Horde, with the mass death of the ruling elite and the administrative class leading to a period of protracted civil war known as the "Great Troubles" (*Zamyatna*), beginning in 1359.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This internal fragmentation, combined with the loss of tax revenue from the depopulated Silk Road trade routes, weakened Mongol authority over its Russian vassals, eventually facilitating the rise of the Grand Duchy of Moscow.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The sudden collapse of the Ilkhanate following the death of its ruler Abu Sa'id in 1335 and turmoil that followed, have been linked to the outbreak of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Tian Shan mountains in Kyrgyzstan was a major node on the trade routes leading directly into the Ilkhanate.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It is biologically plausible that the plague was already hitting nomadic camps and trade hubs before it was recorded by urban chroniclers.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] However, no evidence of mass graves or direct evidence of the plague have been found in the Ilkhanate dating to the early 1330s CE.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] George Childs Kohn, in his *Encyclopedia of Plague and Pestilence*, he explicitly lists 1335 as a potential early date for the plague reaching the Ilkhanate, citing the sudden death of the Khan and his court as circumstantial evidence.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] John France, a military and medieval historian who argues that the "shattering" of the Mongol military machine in the 1330s suggests a massive loss of manpower that political infighting alone cannot explain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Peter Jackson, in The Mongols and the Islamic World, notes the suspicious timing.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] While he remains cautious, he highlights that the "administrative paralysis" following 1335 mirrors the later effects of the Black Death in Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] McNeill, in his seminal work *Plagues and Peoples* (1976), pioneered the theory that the Mongol Empire's trade routes were the primary "caravanserai" for the plague, suggesting the Ilkhanate was the first major urban center to be hit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In 1368, the Fall of the Yuan Dynasty in China was due to the combination of plague, famine, and flooding that weakened Mongol authority, fueling the Red Turban Rebellion (c.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] 1351–1368) that established the Ming Dynasty.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In India, the Tughlaq Dynasty ruled by Muhammad bin Tughlaq (r.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] 1325–1351) does not have records of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] There are records of outbreaks of massive pestilence (waba) around 1334–1335 (Warangal/Bidar Outbreak) and 1344.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] However, there is no clear evidence proving it was due to the Black Death bacterium.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Ibn Battuta provides the primary description of this event at the time the army was stationed near Bidar/Warangal in the Deccan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Waba (Pestilence) was described as a disease that struck with such speed that soldiers would fall dead almost instantly.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] It was reported that nearly half of the royal army perished.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The Sultan himself became critically ill but survived, eventually retreating to Delhi to escape the contagion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The description of the Indian outbreak is somewhat general, focusing more on the suddenness of death and the high fever rather than the distinct physical markers like buboes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This has led some researchers to suggest it may have been a different tropical disease, such as a severe form of malaria or cholera.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] European writers contemporary with the plague described the disease in Latin as *pestis* or *pestilentia*, 'pestilence'; *epidemia*, 'epidemic'; *mortalitas*, 'mortality'.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In English prior to the 18th century, the event was called the "pestilence" or "great pestilence", "the plague" or the "great death".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Subsequent to the pandemic "the *furste moreyn*" (first murrain) or "first pestilence" was applied, to distinguish the mid-14th century phenomenon from other infectious diseases and epidemics of plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The 1347 pandemic plague was not referred to specifically as "black", at the time, in any European language.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The expression "black death" had occasionally been applied to other fatal or dangerous diseases.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In English, "Black death" was not used to describe this plague pandemic, however, until the 1750s; the term is first attested in 1755, where it translated Danish: *den sorte død*, lit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Previously, most European languages had named the pandemic a variant or calque of the Latin: *magna mortalitas*, lit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The phrase 'black death' – describing Death as black – is very old.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Homer used it in the Odyssey to describe the monstrous Scylla, with her mouths "full of black Death" (Ancient Greek: πλεῖοι μέλανος Θανάτοιο, romanized: *pleîoi mélanos Thanátoio*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Seneca the Younger may have been the first to describe an epidemic as 'black death' (Latin: *mors atra*), but only in reference to the acute lethality and dark prognosis of disease.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The 12th–13th century French physician Gilles de Corbeil had already used *atra mors* to refer to a "pestilential fever" (*febris pestilentialis*) in his work *On the Signs and Symptoms of Diseases* (*De signis et symptomatibus aegritudium*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The phrase *mors nigra*, 'black death', was used in 1350 by Simon de Covino (or Couvin), a Belgian astronomer, in his poem "On the Judgement of the Sun at a Feast of Saturn" (*De judicio Solis in convivio Saturni*), which attributes the plague to an astrological conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] His use of the phrase is not connected unambiguously with the plague pandemic of 1347 and appears to refer to the fatal outcome of disease.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The historian Elizabeth Penrose, writing under the pen-name "Mrs Markham", described the 14th-century outbreak as the "black death" in 1823.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The historian Cardinal Francis Aidan Gasquet wrote about the Great Pestilence in 1893 and suggested that it had been "some form of the ordinary Eastern or bubonic plague".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In 1908, Gasquet said use of the name *atra mors* for the 14th-century epidemic first appeared in a 1631 book on Danish history by J.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Pontanus: "Commonly and from its effects, they called it the black death" (Latin: *Vulgo & ab effectu atram mortem vocitabant*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Research from 2017 suggests plague first infected humans in Europe and Asia in the Late Neolithic to Early Bronze Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Research in 2018 found evidence of *Yersinia pestis* in an ancient Swedish tomb, which may have been associated with the "Neolithic decline" around 3000BCE, in which European populations fell significantly.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This *Y. pestis* may have been different from more modern types, with bubonic plague transmissible by fleas first known from Bronze Age remains near Samara.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] The symptoms of bubonic plague are first attested in a fragment of Rufus of Ephesus preserved by Oribasius; these ancient medical authorities suggest bubonic plague had appeared in the Roman Empire before the reign of Trajan, six centuries before arriving at Pelusium in the reign of Justinian I.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] In 2013, researchers confirmed earlier speculation that the cause of the plague of Justinian (541–549, with recurrences until 750) was *Y*.*pestis*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] This is known as the first plague pandemic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p01] Ole Jørgen Benedictow believes that this indicates it was an offshoot of the first plague pandemic which made its way eastward to Chinese territory by around 600.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] A report by the Medical Faculty of Paris stated that a conjunction of planets had caused "a great pestilence in the air" (miasma theory).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Some Muslim doctors cautioned against trying to prevent or treat a disease sent by God.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Others adopted preventive measures and treatments for plague used by Europeans.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] These Muslim doctors also depended on the writings of the ancient Greeks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] , the organism responsible for spreading bubonic plague in most plague epidemics.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] which appears as a dark mass in the gut.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] is regurgitated into the wound, causing infection.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Due to climate change in Asia, rodents began to flee the dried-out grasslands to more populated areas, spreading the disease.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The plague disease, caused by the bacterium *Yersinia pestis*, is enzootic (commonly present) in populations of fleas carried by ground rodents, including marmots, in various areas, including Central Asia, Kurdistan, West Asia, North India, Uganda, and the western United States.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Definitive confirmation of the role of *Y. pestis* arrived in 2010 with a publication in *PLOS Pathogens* by Haensch et al.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] They assessed the presence of DNA/RNA with polymerase chain reaction (PCR) techniques for *Y. pestis* from the tooth sockets in human skeletons from mass graves in northern, central and southern Europe that were associated archaeologically with the Black Death and subsequent resurgences.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 2011 these results were further confirmed with genetic evidence derived from Black Death victims in the East Smithfield burial site in England.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Schuenemann et al. concluded in 2011 "that the Black Death in medieval Europe was caused by a variant of *Y. pestis* that may no longer exist".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Later in 2011, Bos et al. reported in *Nature* the first draft genome of *Y. pestis* from plague victims from the same East Smithfield cemetery and indicated that the strain that caused the Black Death is ancestral to most modern strains of *Y. pestis*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Later genomic papers have further confirmed the phylogenetic placement of the *Y. pestis* strain responsible for the Black Death as both the ancestor of later plague epidemics—including the third plague pandemic—and the descendant of the strain responsible for the Plague of Justinian.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In addition, plague genomes from prehistory have been recovered.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] DNA taken from 25 skeletons from 14th-century London showed that plague is a strain of *Y. pestis* almost identical to that which hit Madagascar in 2013.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Further DNA evidence also proves the role of *Y. pestis* and traces the source to the Tian Shan mountains in Kyrgyzstan.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Researchers are hampered by a lack of reliable statistics from this period.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Most work has been done on the spread of the disease in England, where estimates of overall population at the start of the plague vary by over 100%, as no census was undertaken in England between the time of publication of the Domesday Book of 1086 and the poll tax of the year 1377.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Estimates of plague victims are usually extrapolated from figures for the clergy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Mathematical modelling is used to match the spreading patterns and the means of transmission.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 2018 researchers suggested an alternative model in which "the disease was spread from human fleas and body lice to other people".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The second model claims to better fit the trends of the plague's death toll, as the rat-flea-human hypothesis would have produced a delayed but very high spike in deaths, contradicting historical death data.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The Oriental rat flea has poor survival in cooler climates and reevaluation suggests the human flea was the principal vector of plague epidemics in Northern Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Lars Walløe argued that these authors "take it for granted that Simond's infection model, black rat → rat flea → human, which was developed to explain the spread of plague in India, is the only way an epidemic of *Yersinia pestis* infection could spread".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Similarly, Monica Green has argued that greater attention is needed to the range of (especially non-commensal) animals that might be involved in the transmission of plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] This theory is supported by research in 2018 which suggested transmission was more likely by body lice and fleas during the second plague pandemic.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Academic debate continues, but no single alternative explanation for the plague's spread has achieved widespread acceptance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Many scholars arguing for *Y. pestis* as the major agent of the pandemic suggest that its extent and symptoms can be explained by a combination of bubonic plague with other diseases, including typhus, smallpox, and respiratory infections.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In addition to the bubonic infection, others point to additional septicemic and pneumonic forms of plague, which lengthen the duration of outbreaks throughout the seasons and help account for its high mortality rate and additional recorded symptoms.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 2014, Public Health England announced the results of an examination of 25 bodies exhumed in the Clerkenwell area of London, as well as of wills registered in London during the period, which supported the pneumonic hypothesis.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Currently, while osteoarcheologists have conclusively verified the presence of *Y. pestis* bacteria in burial sites across northern Europe through examination of bones and dental pulp, no other epidemic pathogen has been discovered to bolster the alternative explanations.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to a team of medical geneticists led by Mark Achtman, *Yersinia pestis* "evolved in or near China" over 2,600 years ago.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Later research by a team led by Galina Eroshenko placed its origins more specifically in the Tian Shan mountains on the border between Kyrgyzstan and China.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] However more recent research notes that the previous sampling contained East Asian bias and that sampling since then has discovered strains of *Y. pestis* in the Caucasus region previously thought to be restricted to China.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] There is also no physical or specific textual evidence of the Black Death in 14th century China.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] As a result, China's place in the sequence of the plague's spread is still debated to this day.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to Charles Creighton, records of epidemics in 14th-century China suggest nothing more than typhus and major Chinese outbreaks of epidemic disease post-date the European epidemic by several years.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The earliest Chinese descriptions of the bubonic plague do not appear until the 1640s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Epidemics killed an estimated 25 million across Asia during the fifteen years before the Black Death reached Constantinople in 1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to John Norris, evidence from Issyk-Kul indicates a small sporadic outbreak characteristic of transmission from rodents to humans with no wide-scale effect.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to Achtman, the dating of the plague suggests that it was not carried along the Silk Road, and its widespread appearance in that region probably postdates the European outbreak.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Additionally, the Silk Road had already been heavily disrupted before the spread of the Black Death; Western and Middle Eastern traders found it difficult to trade on the Silk Road by 1325 and impossible by 1340, making its role in the spread of plague less likely.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] There are no records of the symptoms of the Black Death from Mongol sources or writings from travelers east of the Black Sea prior to the Crimean outbreak in 1346.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The theory of Chinese origin implicates the Silk Road, the disease possibly spreading alongside Mongol armies and traders, or possibly arriving via ship—however, this theory is still contested.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] It is speculated that rats aboard Zheng He's ships in the 15th century may have carried the plague to Southeast Asia, India, and Africa.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Research on the Delhi Sultanate and the Yuan dynasty shows no evidence of any serious epidemic in 14th-century India and no specific evidence of plague in 14th-century China, suggesting that the Black Death may not have reached these regions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Ole Benedictow argues that since the first clear reports of the Black Death come from Kaffa, the Black Death most likely originated in the nearby plague focus on the northwestern shore of the Caspian Sea.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Monica Green suggests that other parts of Eurasia outside the west do not contain the same evidence of the Black Death, because there were actually four strains of *Yersinia pestis* that became predominant in different parts of the world.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Mongol records of illness such as food poisoning may have been referring to the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Another theory is that the plague originated near Europe and cycled through the Mediterranean, Northern Europe and Russia before making its way to China.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Other historians, such as John Norris and Ole Benedictaw, believe the plague likely originated in Europe or the Middle East, and never reached China.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Norris specifically argues for an origin in Kurdistan rather than Central Asia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague was reportedly first introduced to Europe via Genoese traders from their port city of Kaffa in the Crimea in 1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] As the disease took hold, Genoese traders fled across the Black Sea to Constantinople, where the disease first arrived in Europe in summer 1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The epidemic there killed the 13-year-old son of the Byzantine emperor, John VI Kantakouzenos, who wrote a description of the disease modelled on Thucydides's account of the 5th century BCE Plague of Athens, noting the spread of the Black Death by ship between maritime cities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Nicephorus Gregoras, while writing to Demetrios Kydones, described the rising death toll, the futility of medicine, and the panic of the citizens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The first outbreak in Constantinople lasted a year, but the disease recurred ten times before 1400.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Carried by twelve Genoese galleys, plague arrived by ship in Sicily in October 1347; the disease spread rapidly all over the island.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Galleys from Kaffa reached Genoa and Venice in January 1348, but it was the outbreak in Pisa a few weeks later that was the entry point into northern Italy.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Towards the end of January, one of the galleys expelled from Italy arrived in Marseilles.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] From Italy, the disease spread northwest across Europe, striking France, Spain, Portugal, and England by June 1348, then spreading east and north through Germany, Scotland and Scandinavia from 1348 to 1350.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] It was introduced into Norway in 1349 when a ship landed at Askøy, then spread to Bjørgvin (modern Bergen).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Finally, it spread to northern Russia in 1352 and reached Moscow in 1353.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague was less common in parts of Europe with less-established trade relations, including the majority of the Basque Country, isolated parts of Belgium and the Netherlands, and isolated Alpine villages throughout the continent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Among many other culprits of plague contagiousness, pre-existing malnutrition weakened the immune response, contributing to an immense decline in European population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The disease struck various regions in the Middle East and North Africa during the pandemic, leading to serious depopulation and permanent change in both economic and social structures.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] By autumn 1347, plague had reached Alexandria in Egypt, transmitted by sea from Constantinople via a single merchant ship carrying slaves.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] By late summer 1348, it reached Cairo, capital of the Mamluk Sultanate, cultural center of the Islamic world, and the largest city in the Mediterranean Basin; the Bahriyya child sultan an-Nasir Hasan fled and more than a third of the 600,000 residents died.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The Nile was choked with corpses despite Cairo having a medieval hospital, the late 13th-century bimaristan of the Qalawun complex.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The historian al-Maqrizi described the abundant work for grave-diggers and practitioners of funeral rites; plague recurred in Cairo more than fifty times over the following one and a half centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] During 1347, the disease travelled eastward to Gaza by April; by July it had reached Damascus, and in October plague had broken out in Aleppo.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] That year, in the territory of modern Lebanon, Syria, Israel, and Palestine, the cities of Ascalon, Acre, Jerusalem, Sidon, and Homs were all infected.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 1348–1349, the disease reached Antioch.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The city's residents fled to the north, but most of them ended up dying during the journey.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The pandemic spread westwards from Alexandria along the African coast, while in April 1348 Tunis was infected by ship from Sicily.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Tunis was then under attack by an army from Morocco; this army dispersed in 1348 and brought the contagion with them to Morocco, whose epidemic may also have been seeded from the Islamic city of Almería in al-Andalus.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Mecca became infected in 1348 by pilgrims performing the Hajj.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 1351 or 1352, the Rasulid sultan of the Yemen, al-Mujahid Ali, was released from Mamluk captivity in Egypt and carried plague with him on his return home.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] During 1349, records show the city of Mosul suffered a massive epidemic, and the city of Baghdad experienced a second round of the disease.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Symptoms of the plague include fever of 38–41 °C (100–106 °F), headaches, painful aching joints, nausea and vomiting, and a general feeling of malaise.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Left untreated, 80% of victims die within eight days.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Contemporary accounts of the pandemic are varied and often imprecise.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The most commonly noted symptom was the appearance of buboes (or *gavocciolos*) in the groin, neck and armpits, which oozed pus and bled when opened.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] This was followed by acute fever and vomiting of blood.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Most people died two to seven days after initial infection.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Freckle-like spots and rashes, which may have been caused by flea-bites, were identified as another potential sign of plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Lodewijk Heyligen, whose master Cardinal Giovanni Colonna died of plague in 1348, noted a distinct form of the disease, pneumonic plague, that infected the lungs and led to respiratory problems.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Symptoms include fever, cough and blood-tinged sputum.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] As the disease progresses, sputum becomes free-flowing and bright red.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Pneumonic plague has a mortality rate of 90–95%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Septicemic plague is the least common of the three forms, with an untreated mortality rate near 100%.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Symptoms are high fevers and purple skin patches (purpura due to disseminated intravascular coagulation).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In cases of pneumonic and particularly septicemic plague, the progress of the disease is so rapid that there would often be no time for the development of the enlarged lymph nodes that were noted as buboes.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] There are no exact figures for the death toll; the rate varied widely by locality.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Urban centers with higher populations suffered longer periods of abnormal mortality.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Some estimate that it may have killed between 75,000,000 and 200,000,000 people in Eurasia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] A study published in 2022 of pollen samples across Europe from 1250 to 1450 was used to estimate changes in agricultural output before and after the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The authors found great variability in different regions, with evidence for high mortality in areas of Scandinavia, France, western Germany, Greece, and central Italy, but uninterrupted agricultural growth in central and eastern Europe, Iberia, and Ireland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The Black Death killed, by various estimations, from 25 to 60% of Europe's population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Robert Gottfried writes that as early as 1351, "agents for Pope Clement VI calculated the number of dead in Christian Europe at 23,840,000.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] With a preplague population of about 75 million, Clement's figure accounts for mortality of 31%-a rate about midway between the 50% mortality estimated for East Anglia, Tuscany, and parts of Scandinavia, and the less-than-15% morbidity for Bohemia and Galicia.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] And it is unerringly close to Froissart's claim that "a third of the world died," a measurement probably drawn from St.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] John's figure of mortality from plague in the Book of Revelation, a favorite medieval source of information." Ole J.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Benedictow proposes 60% mortality rate for Europe as a whole based on available data, with up to 80% based on poor nutritional conditions in the 14th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to medieval historian Philip Daileader, it is likely that over four years, 45–50% of the European population died of plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The overwhelming number of deaths in Europe sometimes made mass burials necessary, and some sites had hundreds or thousands of bodies.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The mass burial sites that have been excavated have allowed archaeologists to continue interpreting and defining the biological, sociological, historical, and anthropological implications of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The mortality rate of the Black Death in the 14th century was far greater than the worst 20th-century outbreaks of *Y. pestis* plague, which occurred in India and killed as much as 3% of the population of certain cities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 1348, the disease spread so rapidly that nearly a third of the European population perished before any physicians or government authorities had time to reflect upon its origins.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In crowded cities, it was not uncommon for as much as 50% of the population to die.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Half of Paris's population of 100,000 people died.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In Italy, the population of Florence was reduced from between 110,000 and 120,000 inhabitants in 1338 to 50,000 in 1351.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] At least 60% of the population of Hamburg and Bremen perished, and a similar percentage of Londoners may have died from the disease as well, leaving a death toll of approximately 62,000 between 1346 and 1353.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Florence's tax records suggest that 80% of the city's population died within four months in 1348.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Before 1350, there were about 170,000 settlements in Germany, and this was reduced by nearly 40,000 by 1450.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The disease bypassed some areas, with the most isolated areas being less vulnerable to contagion.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague did not appear in Flanders until the turn of the 15th century, and the impact was less severe on the populations of Hainaut, Finland, northern Germany, and areas of Poland.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Monks, nuns, and priests were especially hard-hit since they cared for people ill with the plague.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The level of mortality in the rest of Eastern Europe was likely similar to that of Western Europe in the first outbreak, with descriptions suggesting a similar effect on Russian towns, and the cycles of plague in Russia being roughly equivalent.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In 1382, the physician to the Avignon Papacy, Raimundo Chalmel de Vinario (Latin: *Magister Raimundus*, lit.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] 'Master Raymond'), observed the decreasing mortality rate of successive outbreaks of plague in 1347–1348, 1362, 1371 and 1382 in his treatise *On Epidemics* (*De epidemica*).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] By the 1380s in Europe, the plague predominantly affected children.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Chalmel de Vinario recognised that bloodletting was ineffective (though he continued to prescribe bleeding for members of the Roman Curia, whom he disliked), and said that all true cases of plague were caused by astrological factors and were incurable; he was never able to effect a cure.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The populations of some Italian cities, notably Florence, did not regain their pre-14th century size until the 19th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The Black Death killed about 40% of Egypt's population.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In Cairo, with a population numbering as many as 600,000, and possibly the largest city west of China, between one third and 40% of the inhabitants died within eight months.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] By the 18th century, the population of Cairo was halved from its numbers in 1347.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] It has been suggested that the Black Death, like other outbreaks through history, disproportionately affected the poorest people and those already in worse physical condition than the wealthier citizens.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] But along with population decline from the pandemic, wages soared in response to a subsequent labour shortage.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] However, many labourers, artisans, and craftsmen—those living from money-wages alone—suffered a reduction in real incomes owing to rampant inflation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Landowners were also pushed to substitute monetary rents for labour services in an effort to keep tenants.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Taxes and tithes became difficult to collect, with living poor refusing to cover the share of the rich deceased, because many properties were empty and unfarmed, and because tax-collectors, where they could be employed, refused to go to plague spots.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The trade disruptions in the Mongol Empire caused by the Black Death was one of the reasons for its collapse.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] A study performed by Thomas Van Hoof of the Utrecht University suggests that the innumerable deaths brought on by the pandemic cooled the climate by freeing up land and triggering reforestation.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] This may have led to the Little Ice Age.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Renewed religious fervor and fanaticism increased in the wake of the Black Death.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Some Europeans targeted "various groups such as Jews, friars, foreigners, beggars, pilgrims", lepers, and Romani, blaming them for the crisis.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Lepers, and others with skin diseases such as acne or psoriasis, were killed throughout Europe.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Because 14th-century healers and governments were at a loss to explain or stop the disease, Europeans turned to astrological forces, earthquakes and the poisoning of wells by Jews as possible reasons for outbreaks.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Many believed the epidemic was a punishment by God for their sins, and could be relieved by winning God's forgiveness.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] There were many attacks against Jewish communities.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In the Strasbourg massacre of February 1349, about 2,000 Jews were murdered.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In August 1349, the Jewish communities in Mainz and Cologne were annihilated.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] By 1351, 60 major and 150 smaller Jewish communities had been destroyed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] During this period many Jews relocated to Poland, where they received a welcome from King Casimir the Great.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] One theory that has been advanced is that the Black Death's devastation of Florence, between 1348 and 1350, resulted in a shift in the world view of people in 14th-century Italy that ultimately led to the Renaissance.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Italy was particularly badly hit by the pandemic, and the resulting familiarity with death may have caused thinkers to dwell more on their lives on Earth, rather than on spirituality and the afterlife.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] It has also been argued that the Black Death prompted a new wave of piety, manifested in the sponsorship of religious works of art.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] This does not fully explain why the Renaissance occurred in Italy in the 14th century; the Renaissance's emergence was most likely the result of the complex interaction of the above factors, in combination with an influx of Greek scholars after the fall of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] As a result of the drastic reduction in the populace the value of the working class increased, and commoners came to enjoy more freedom.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] To answer the increased need for labour, workers travelled in search of the most favorable position economically.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Prior to the emergence of the Black Death, the continent was considered a feudalistic society, composed of fiefs and city-states frequently managed by the Catholic Church.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The pandemic completely restructured both religion and political forces; survivors began to turn to other forms of spirituality and the power dynamics of the fiefs and city-states crumbled.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The survivors of the pandemic found not only that the prices of food were lower but also that lands were more abundant, and many of them inherited property from their dead relatives, and this probably contributed to the destabilization of feudalism.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The word "quarantine" has its roots in this period, though the practice of isolating people to prevent the spread of disease is older.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In the city-state of Ragusa (modern Dubrovnik, Croatia), a thirty-day isolation period was implemented in 1377 for new arrivals to the city from plague-affected areas.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The isolation period was later extended to forty days, and given the name "quarantino" from the Italian word for "forty".
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Smaller monasteries and convents became unviable and closed.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Up to half parish churches lost their priest, apart from the parishioners.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The plague repeatedly returned to haunt Europe and the Mediterranean throughout the 14th to 17th centuries.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] According to Jean-Noël Biraben, the plague was present somewhere in Europe in every year between 1346 and 1671 (although some researchers have cautions about the uncritical use of Biraben's data).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Subsequent outbreaks, though severe, marked the plague's retreat from most of Europe (18th century) and North Africa (19th century).
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Historian George Sussman argued that the plague had not occurred in East Africa until the 20th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] However, other sources suggest that the second pandemic did indeed reach sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] More than 1.25 million deaths resulted from the extreme incidence of plague in 17th-century Spain.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The Black Death ravaged much of the Islamic world.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague could be found in the Islamic world almost every year between 1500 and 1850.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Sometimes the outbreaks affected small areas, while other outbreaks affected multiple regions.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague repeatedly struck the cities of North Africa.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Cairo suffered more than fifty plague epidemics within 150 years from the plague's first appearance, with the final outbreak of the second pandemic there in the 1840s.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Plague remained a major event in Ottoman society until the second quarter of the 19th century.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Between 1701 and 1750, thirty-seven larger and smaller epidemics were recorded in Constantinople, and an additional thirty-one between 1751 and 1800.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Baghdad has suffered severely from visitations of the plague, and sometimes two-thirds of its population died.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The third plague pandemic (1855–1960) started in China in the mid-19th century, spreading to all inhabited continents and killing 10 million people in India alone.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The investigation of the pathogen that caused the 19th-century plague was begun by teams of scientists who visited Hong Kong in 1894, among whom was the French-Swiss bacteriologist Alexandre Yersin, for whom the pathogen was named.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Twelve plague outbreaks in Australia between 1900 and 1925 resulted in over 1,000 deaths, chiefly in Sydney.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] This led to the establishment of a Public Health Department there which undertook some leading-edge research on plague transmission from rat fleas to humans via the bacillus *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] The first North American plague epidemic was the San Francisco plague of 1900–1904, followed by another outbreak in 1907–1908.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Treatment methods include insecticides, the use of antibiotics, and a plague vaccine.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] It is feared that the plague bacterium could develop drug resistance and again become a major health threat.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] One case of a drug-resistant form of the bacterium was found in Madagascar in 1995.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] Another outbreak in Madagascar was reported in November 2014.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] In October 2017, the deadliest outbreak of the plague in modern times hit Madagascar, killing 170 people and infecting thousands.
[src:agriculture-in-scotland-in-the-middle-ages/black-death-p02] An estimate of the case fatality rate for the modern plague, after the introduction of antibiotics, is 11%, although it may be higher in underdeveloped regions.
